'''Vusumzi L. Make''' (1931 &ndash; 15 April 2006)<ref name="sahistory">{{cite web |url= http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/vusimuzi-vusi-linda-make|title= Vus'umuzi Make|accessdate=2007-01-06|work= sahistory.org.za|publisher= South African History Online}}</ref> was a [[South Africa]]n civil rights activist and lawyer.<ref name="etd.rau4">{{cite web| url = http://etd.rau.ac.za/theses/available/etd-08182004-115716/restricted/FinalChapter4.pdf| title = The generation of strained intra-PAC relations in exile 1962-1990| accessdate = 2006-12-27| last = Kondlo| first = Kwandiwe Merriman| date = 2004-01-01| work = In the twilight of the Azanian Revolution: the exile history of the Pan Africanist Congress of Azania (South Africa): (1960-1990)| publisher = University of Johannesburg| pages = Chapter 4, pp 146–246}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He and the [[United States|American]] poet [[Maya Angelou]] met in 1961,<ref name="Random House">{{cite book|author1=Gillespie, Marcia Ann|author2=Butler, Rosa Johnson |author3=Long, Richard A.|date= 2008|title= Maya Angelou: A Glorious Celebration|location= New York| publisher= Random House| isbn= 978-0-385-51108-7 |page= 59}}</ref><ref name="drake">{{cite web| url = http://drake.marin.k12.ca.us/stuwork/comacad/poets/ANGELOU/bio.html| title = The Life and Times of Maya Angelou| accessdate = 2006-12-27| publisher = Sir Francis Drake High School| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070208033802/http://drake.marin.k12.ca.us/stuwork/comacad/poets/ANGELOU/bio.html| archive-date = 8 February 2007| dead-url = yes| df = dmy-all}}</ref> lived together in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], and parted ways in 1962.<ref name="Random House"/><ref name="ark">{{cite web| url = http://encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=1085 | title = Maya Angelou (1928–)| accessdate = 2006-12-27| last = Mcgraw| first = Patricia Washington| date = 2006-07-12| work = Encyclopedia of Arkansas| publisher = Central Arkansas Library System}}</ref> He was a professor at the [[University of Liberia]] in [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]] from 1968 to 1974.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

==Time in the Pan Africanist Congress==
When [[Potlako Leballo]], Chairman of the [[Pan Africanist Congress]], was forced out of the position, Make joined a Presidential Council consisting of [[David Sibeko]], [[Ellias Ntloedibe]], and himself. Several months later, Make became the sole Chairman.<ref name="etd.rau6">{{cite web| url = http://etd.rau.ac.za/theses/available/etd-08182004-115716/restricted/FinalChapter6.pdf| title = From Poqo to APLA: The evolution of the PAC’s military strategy (1961-1990)| accessdate = 2006-12-27| last = Kondlo| first = Kwandiwe Merriman| date = 2004-01-01| work = In the twilight of the Azanian Revolution: the exile history of the Pan Africanist Congress of Azania (South Africa): (1960-1990)| publisher = University of Johannesburg| pages = 281–311| chapter = 6}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He resigned from the chairmanship in January 1981 to make way for [[John Nyathi Pokela]], who had been recently imprisoned on [[Robben Island]]. Under Pokela, Make served as deputy chairman of the PAC.<ref name="etd.rau4"/>

==Death==
Make died on 15 April 2006 in [[Pretoria]].<ref name="sahistory"/> He was survived by his widow Alma Liziwe Make and daughter Titise.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

